About
Refreshing and irrepressibly raunchy, ABSINTHE is an intoxicating cocktail of jaw-dropping adult circus, burlesque and vaudeville, remixed and reimagined to tease, please and delight even cynical, seen-it-all audiences. So mark your calendars, mask up and wash your freakin' hands, because January 16th, the "#1 greatest show in Las Vegas history" (Las Vegas Weekly) returns to stage, as staggeringly sexy, death-defyingly thrilling and off-the-wall hilarious as you remember—and a zillion times safer than you’d expect. Unapologetically outrageous and undeniably absurd, Absinthe is for ages 18 and above.
Duration: 1-2 hours

  • Arlene
    Edinburgh, United Kingdom13 contributions
    Rude, crude and utterly hilarious...
    Utterly amazing and hilarious show. If you're easily offended or even not so easily offended, then beware! Leave your prudishness at the door as there'll be bad language, disgusting (but hilarious) jokes and maybe even full monologues about intimate acts! The acrobats, dancers, strongmen and contortionists were utterly fantastic and very engaging! Pretty much a circus of amazing people for mature (or extremely immature) adults only! The seating is quirky. Mismatched cushioned and hard metal seats in a circle around the stage and it's a bit squished but it lends itself to the quirky circus vibe. Just be ready to touch the person next to you if you're a bit bigger! However, there's not bad place to sit and you should be able to see from anywhere. "The Gazillionaire" MC was fun and brutal on people in the first three rows so if you can't take a joke or don't like attention, sit further back! All in all, a fantastic night out and one of the better shows we seen in Vegas.

  • HimeNoHogosha
    Santa Clara, California97 contributions
    A raunchy show in an intimate tent setting
    I enjoyed this show a lot, and can understand why many reviewers recommend this as a top "must see" show. There wasn't any nudity, but the performances and jokes were definitely very raunchy. The acts were very good, with my least favorite being the tap dancing. If you're sitting in the inner circle, you are definitely in the splash zone; literally splashes from an act with water, but also figuratively as in the emcee is likely to pick on you as part of the crowd work. The venue is small and intimate, you will definitely be able to see the acts from anywhere you sit. I do recommend sitting in the sections to the left or the right of the entrance (I think that gives a better view of the performers). The chairs are just assorted, but from what I could tell the ones closer to the middle are pushed more tightly together and look uncushioned. We had heavy coats to deal with the very cold outside temperature, but we were able to take them off inside the tent where it was very comfortable.

I have never seen anything like this, and we have seen many shows. First, we were told to avoid front row seats, which we had purchased but were able to change. Luckily, he only addressed us once. Others were not so lucky. The acrobatics were unbelievable, skaters, and ropes with people swinging wildly about. Everyone in the show had the best bodies and skill we have ever seen.
There is a woman with a crazy outfit on who has exchanges with the host. She says some pretty weird, nasty stuff.

The seats are all different metal chairs that look like they came from a dump. Very uncomfortable, believe it or not you forget about the discomfort when the show starts. There were some high tops as well. We did not have drinks so I cannot speak to the pricing. I am sure it like everywhere else in Vegas.

We really enjoyed the show and the talent is amazing. We are glad we went even though the host asked our friend if he picked us (his wife and me) up in the parking lot of Cracker Barrel. He didn't see my husband and thought the 3 of us were together. He left us alone after that.
People who got up on the stage at the hosts beckoning, well let's just say. WOW.

Amazing, hilarious, and raunchy - not a kids show
Nov 2024 • Friends
I saw this show something like 6 years ago and remembered it being great, but when a college buddy of mine came out to Vegas for a conference, we met up and went. This show is so much better than I even remember it then, and I loved it back then. Now the show has more of a comfortable waiting area where there used to just be concrete. Now there are some tables, food trucks, and a speakeasy bar. Staff was friendly. The show was amazing in ways hard to describe (if you have a sense of humor). It starts with the Gazillionaire - the foul mouthed, greasy, smarmy, and don't forget foul mouthed - "owner" of the private circus. His sister is just as raunchy but she sneaks up on you with her cute outfit and squeaky voice. If you sit in the first row, you will be picked on and you will get wet. We were six rows back and could see everything and many of the acts were no more than 20 feet from us hanging from ropes and silks and flexible poles, etc. There isn't nudity but there are plenty of people in skimpy outfits. Drinks are not cheap (it's a show in Vegas, of course they aren't) but they are good. I had a good Sazerac cocktail. I look forward to coming back again, and hopefully it won't take me 6+ years to do it.

LawIslander
Philadelphia, Pennsylvania
14 contributions
I bought tickets through a discount website (plumbenefits) the night before the event and ended up with excellent tickets for roughly $90 each (after taxes and fees). Just keep in mind that if you buy online, while you're in Las Vegas, that you'll need to print the voucher and head over to the box office to pick up the physical tickets. If you're picking up with a voucher from a discounter, your seats sometimes aren't assigned until you pick up the tickets, so it probably benefits you to pick them up earlier in the day.
